article.description: DeWanna Bonner had 18 points and nine rebounds to help No. 6 Auburn coast to an 81-54 victory over Alabama on Sunday.
article.headline: Bonner contributes 18 as fifth-ranked Tigers roll Tide
article.linkText: Bonner powers Auburn's blowout of Alabama
article.story:
TUSCALOOSA, Ala. -- Auburn hustled, rebounded and ran away with an easy victory.

DeWanna Bonner had 18 points and nine rebounds to help the Tigers (No. 5 ESPN/USA Today, No. 6 AP) coast to an 81-54 victory over Alabama on Sunday, back to winning in dominant fashion after three somewhat shaky performances.

"That was the most complete game that we've played all year long and it came at the right time," Tigers coach Nell Fortner said. "We kind of went through a little bit of a lull there.

"I don't know if we've ever outrebounded a team like that this year. We were just very aggressive today."

Whitney Boddie added 12 points and 12 assists for the Tigers (23-1, 8-1 Southeastern Conference), who led by 26 points at halftime. Sherell Hobbs scored 16 points.

The Tigers held a 51-29 rebounding edge and did most of their scoring around the basket. They also beat Alabama (12-12, 0-9) to most of the loose balls, collecting 21 offensive rebounds.

"We just came out more aggressive," said Bonner, who had five offensive boards. "We kind of came out with the mentality to protect the basket and rebound. We kind of got back to our old game."

Auburn has won 11 of the last 12 meetings against its in-state rival, including seven in a row. The Tide, meanwhile, has dropped 22 consecutive SEC games.

"They showed us why they're a Top 10 team," Alabama's Varisia Raffington said. "They go after loose balls and hustle all the time."

The Tigers had struggled to wins over LSU and Mississippi after suffering their first loss of the season at Georgia. They took control of this one early.

Auburn held Alabama to only two field goals over the final 12 minutes of the first half for a 47-21 lead. The Tigers scored the final eight points before halftime to cap their highest scoring opening half in an SEC game this season.

Bonner made all eight free throw attempts for Auburn, which hit just one of eight 3-pointers.

Boddie controlled the game in the first half, logging 10 points and 10 assists. She didn't commit a turnover in the game.

"Boddie is the person who I think really made the big difference," Tide coach Wendell Hudson said. "Her penetration opened up baskets for other players."

The Tigers had 10 players log double-digit minutes.

Tierney Jenkins led Alabama with 13 points and seven rebounds. Raffington also had 13 points for the Tide, while Ericka Russell added 11.

Auburn shot 49 percent while holding Alabama to 34 percent.

Jenkins felt the Tide was outhustled.

"I don't think the effort was there at all," she said. "They were getting loose balls that were ours. If you play a good team and don't have the effort, there's no way you can win. That's what happened today."
